  "text": "arPHA1 is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous loss-of-function mutations in genes that encode subunits of endothelial sodium channel (ENaC) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ; the absence of electrogenic sodium reabsorption in the cortical collecting tubule in arPHA1 inhibits normal potassium and hydrogen ion secretion, leading to the characteristic metabolic acidosis and life-threatening hyperkalemia. In contrast, autosomal dominant PHA1 (adPHA1; OMIM #177735) is considered a mild disease [CITATION_3] . Patients may be asymptomatic or ill at birth from renal salt wasting, but they do not require sodium supplementation after early childhood. We previously demonstrated that heterozygous mutations in the gene that encodes the mineralocorticoid receptor (MR) cause adPHA1. We identified heterozygous nonsense, frameshift, and splicing mutations in MR in independent kindreds with adPHA1 (5). More recently, a variety of diseasecausing mutations in MR, including missense mutations in the hormone-binding domain of the receptor that prevent the re-ceptor from binding to its cognate ligand aldosterone, have been identified (6 -9) .",
